04965nam a22006495i 9780814737965DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t19991999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780814737965  a(DE-B1597)550560  a(OCoLC)45844128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV6452.N72b.J336 1999 7aPOL0050002bisacsh04a364.40974711 aJacobs, James B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGotham Unbound :bHow New York City Was Liberated From the Grip of Organized Crime /cJames B. Jacobs, Coleen Friel, Robert Raddick. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. An Introduction to the Place and the Players -- tPART I: THE “MOBBING-UP” OF NEW YORK CITY -- t2. A Cosa Nostra Outfit -- t3. Fishy Business -- t4. The Taking of John F.Kennedy Airport -- t5. Exhibiting Corruption -- t6. Carting Away a Fortune -- t7. Building a Cosa Nostra Fiefdom -- t8. Conclusion to Part I -- tPART II: THE LIBERATION OF NEW YORK CITY -- t9. Liberating the Garment District -- t10. Freeing the Fulton Fish Market -- t11. Purging the Mob from John F.Kennedy Airport -- t12. Ridding the Javits Convention Center of Organized Crime -- t13. Defeating Cosa Nostra in the Waste-Hauling Industry -- t14. Cleansing the Construction Industry -- t15. Conclusion to Part II -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Names -- tList of Indictments and Judicial Decisions -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCosa Nostra. Organized crime. The Mob. Call it what you like, no other crime group has infiltrated labor unions and manipulated legitimate industries like Italian organized crime families. One cannot understand the history and political economy of New York City-or most other major American cities-in the 20th century without focusing on the role of organized crime in the urban power structure. Gotham Unbound demonstrates the remarkable range of Cosa Nostra's activities and influence and convincingly argues that 20th century organized crime has been no minor annoyance at the periphery of society but a major force in the core economy, acting as a power broker, even as an alternative government in many sectors of the urban economy.James B. Jacobs presents the first comprehensive account of the ways in which the Cosa Nostra infiltrated key sectors of New York City's legitimate economic life and how this came over the years to be accepted as inevitable, in some cases even beneficial. The first half of Gotham Unbound is devoted to the ways organized crime became entrenched in six economic sectors and institutions of the city-the garment district, Fulton Fish Market, freight at JFK airport, construction, the Jacob Javits Convention Center, and the waste-hauling industry. The second half compellingly documents the campaign to purge the mob from unions, industries, and economic sectors, focusing on the unrelenting law enforcement efforts and the central role of Rudolph Giuliani's mayoral administration in devising innovative regulatory strategies to combat the mob.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh1 aFriel, Coleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRaddick, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081474246440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814737965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/i